\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/artin.dimensionone}{Dirichlet character associated with a 1-dimensional Artin representation}}
\begin{definition}\label{artin.dimensionone}
\uses{artin,character.dirichlet,nf.abelian}
A one-dimensional \hyperref[artin]{Artin representation} $\rho:\Gal(\overline{\Q}/\Q)\to \GL_1(\C)\cong \C^\times$.  Since the image is abelian and every Artin representation factors through the Galois group of a number field, we can view $\rho$ as a map $\Gal(K/\Q)\to \C^\times$ for an \hyperref[nf.abelian]{abelian} number field $K$.  

By the Kronecker-Weber theorem, $K$ is contained in a cyclotomic extension $\Q(\zeta_n)$ for some positive integer $n$.  Using the canonical isomorphism $\Gal(\Q(\zeta_n)/\Q)\cong(\Z/n\Z)^\times$, the Artin representation corresponds to a homomorphism $(\Z/n\Z)^\times\to \C^\times$.  

Extending it to $\Z/n\Z$ by defining it to be $0$ off of $(\Z/n\Z)^\times$, and then viewing it as a function on $\Z$ via the natural map $\Z\to\Z/n\Z$, we get the corresponding \hyperref[character.dirichlet]{Dirichlet character}, whose modulus is the same as that of the one-dimensional Artin representation.
\end{definition}


